My friend googled the nearest place with happy hours and El Kallejon came up as an option. We arrived to this House of hoarder and pretty much sat ourselves. We asked about the happy hours and they said they didn't have one. We were already seated so we gave it the benefit of a doubt and stayed. We order white sangria for starts, we were disappointed immediately by the presentation due to the fact it had a mint in and a slice of orange. We looked over the menu, everything was very different for this Mexican infusion ?  but we still picked the most appealing to us. We asked about the specials and whatever she read off her personal handbook sounded like one long gibberish of just one special. We ordered La Gringa and Harlem Style in laymans terms tasteless shrimp, chorizo, pineapple, cheese something. Then when it came to our second round my friend got a whiskey n I wanted a margarita, I asked what other flavors and the waitress sounded unsure proceeded to read off the drunk menu (tamarindo, hibiscus flowers, herbs, rose petals, jalapeno, chilly peppers) to us still sounding unsure. For a place that isn't that big they're attentiveness wasn't so great either. Finally got my margarita, and didn't get salt on the rim like a asked for. Right when we asked for the check they offered postre, my friend decided why not and got the arroz con leche. The look of confusion came over us by this what look like a small cup molding with sprinkles and green paste, my friend tasted it and was even more disappointed by the lack of taste, still don't know why it had sprinkles and once again an unnecessary mint paste at the bottom. When we finally got the bill we were appalled by how extremely expensive it was for tasteless, unsatisfying, unfilling, other than okay plate presentation it definitely wasn't worth the cost. I will never come back nor will I recommend this place to any one else.  I don't normally do reviews but this place definitely called for a bad review!

This place is a hidden gem! If you're not looking, you could pass this little nook and miss out on a great food experience, as the outdoor display isn't noteworthy. While the spot is tiny, there's tons of cultural charm lining the walls and there's an outdoor space in the back, although it wasn't open when I went.  This is a tapas spot, so don't look to be full after ordering an "entree" but be prepared for magic in your mouth. I tried to alter an item on the menu, to which I was promptly told no because it would change the flavor, and I'm so happy I trusted the receipe design of each plate. I had the guacamole and chips for an appetizer, and the Chabela for my entree and every item I tasted was clearly made with love. Everything was so well seasoned!  If I wasn't a believer in "good things take time," I might have been a little annoyed at how long my food took to get to the table. But the food was so good though that it was worth the wait. If you are in a rush, this is not your place. But if you are looking for a meal your palate will undoubtedly enjoy, you'll find it here.

He was more concerned about what the place looked like than actual customers that’s walked in. Which is understandable the place was impeccable I guess. He seemed to be the only one serving and decided to take pictures of a dish and of himself “eating and drinking” on a table(I’m assuming for advertising reasons) while customers were waiting for their orders. Before that he moved the customer that was sitting on that exact table across the room after  the customer was already sitting there. Their signature sangria was watered down not worth $9 and the beer was warm borderline hot. Although the guacamole and flatbreads were good, there was no authenticity of cultures taste. Unfortunately I  wouldn’t go back. :(

I cannot reccomend El Kallejon enough.  I am in the restaurant industry and never write reviews on yelp, but I haven't had a truly memorable restaurant experience in a while and I feel that it is important to let people know that this place is truly exceptional. The owner is passionate and you can taste the passion in the housemade cocktails they produce and the authentic food they serve.  He is fearless and boldly puts out beutiful, well known ingredients in addition to the tasty and unique on the plate.  There is something for everyone on the menu; something for the traditionalist and something for the advenurer.  The prices are beyond resonable for the quality.  The plates are small and meant to be shared; guests get to expereince a taste of many flovors and textures.  In my mind, this is a destination place for those who live in another neighborhood.  For those who are close by, you are the luckiest of all.  I will be back as soon as possible.

The kind of place you wish exists --and here it is! The service is kindly and welcoming, the ambiance charming and artsy, and the food is disarmingly amazing! Their guacamole el Kallejon  with bits of seafood and clam juice will make you never want for this appetizer any other way ever again.  The delicate, yet pronounced fusion of flavors, the freshest/highest quality of ingredients, (the marlin melange could have been delivered more heated; it would have added to the enjoyment of the dish) includes not only the execution of the tapas, but to the cocktails and sangrias.

I've enjoyed every food item we've ordered. The way the tastes are balanced between sweet & savory and the textures soft, crunchy, melty-- You can tell someone put a lot of thought into designing each piece. Definitely have to get the kallejon guacamole and fish tacos. My fave! Guna miss this place when we leave NYC soon. Also, the goat cheese dessert was also delicious, something I wouldn't normally order, but so happy I did!
